<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Before the 18th century, when nationalism emerged as a distinctive movement, states usually were based on religious or dynastic ties; citizens owed loyalty to their church or ruling family. Concerned with clan, tribe, village, or province, people rarely extended their interests nationwide.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A similar problem now, but on a smaller scale. Now most people are extending loyalty to their nation, but rarely doing so to the world at large. It's all about what WE want and what WE need. (We in general sense, not one particular nation.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Historically, the tendency toward nationalism was fostered by various technological, cultural, political, and economic advances. Improvement in communications extended the knowledge of people beyond their village or province. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Much like now. Communications are MUCH more advanced than ever before, and we have more access to people beyond our own country.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Through education, people learned of their common background and tradition and began to identify themselves with the historical continuity of the nation. The introduction of national constitutions and the struggle for political rights gave peoples the sense of helping to determine their fate as a nation and of sharing responsibility for the future well-being of that nation.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Just replace nation with world. Again, nothing wrong with pride in your nation or cultural background, but there's a larger picture. And even nationalistic people consider themselves a part of smaller communities, such as states, cities, or even smaller communities. I don't see why it would be any different if we shifted from nationalism. Ties to your country wouldn't disappear, but people wouldn have a better view of the large picture.<br>
